            ">Gorilla Glue</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/bh-dec-5-1.jpg" alt="Gorilla Glue" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          Mark Singer’s journey with Gorilla Glue is a masterclass in turning a niche product into a global household name. Founded in 1999, Gorilla Glue began its rise to fame with a single, remarkable product: a polyurethane adhesive originally used in Indonesian woodworking. Singer identified its potential for broader consumer use, envisioning it as a solution to DIY enthusiasts and professionals' challenges.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">
          The secret sauce? Gorilla Glue’s unmatched versatility. It could bond wood, metal, glass, ceramics, and more. Unlike competitors, it was waterproof and temperature-resistant, perfect for tough jobs indoors and outdoors. This set Gorilla Glue apart in a crowded adhesive market, where most products were specialized and lacked universal appeal.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Mark Singer’s branding decisions were just as strategic. The Gorilla logo symbolized strength and durability, instantly resonating with consumers. The name was bold and memorable, standing out in a market dominated by technical-sounding brands. The product's tagline, “For the Toughest Jobs on Planet Earth,” further cemented its identity as the go-to choice for reliability.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Marketing wasn’t limited to catchy branding. Singer prioritized educating customers. The packaging was designed with clear instructions, and the company invested in demonstrations to show how Gorilla Glue outperformed alternatives. Word-of-mouth played a huge role, with satisfied customers becoming the brand's most influential ambassadors.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">By the early 2000s, Gorilla Glue had expanded its portfolio, introducing Gorilla Tape, Gorilla Super Glue, and mounting adhesives. Each product adhered to the same principles: quality, durability, and ease of use. Gorilla Tape, in particular, became a sensation, challenging traditional duct tape with its superior grip and weather resistance.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.4">Financially, Gorilla Glue’s growth has been staggering. Reports estimate the brand generates hundreds of millions in annual revenue. Its dominance in the adhesive market has led to partnerships with major retailers like Home Depot, Walmart, and Amazon, ensuring its products are always within reach.</p>
          </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
